Now I have a comprehensive picture of TigerBeetle's assertion patterns. Let me compile the full analysis.

---

## How TigerBeetle Uses `assert` in `init` and FFI Boundary Functions

TigerBeetle's Zig codebase is one of the best references for rigorous assertion discipline at FFI boundaries. The patterns fall into five distinct categories.

---

### 1. Comptime Structural Assertions — Layout Verification Before Any Runtime Code Runs

The most distinctive pattern: before any init can even be called, TigerBeetle uses `comptime { assert(...) }` blocks to guarantee ABI-compatibility between the Zig-internal type and the C-visible opaque type. This runs at compile time, not at runtime.

In [`tb_client_exports.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/clients/c/tb_client_exports.zig#L18-L23):

```zig
pub const tb_client_t = extern struct {
    @"opaque": [4]u64,

    comptime {
        assert(@sizeOf(tb_client_t) == @sizeOf(tb.ClientInterface));
        assert(@bitSizeOf(tb_client_t) == @bitSizeOf(tb.ClientInterface));
        assert(@alignOf(tb_client_t) == @alignOf(tb.ClientInterface));
    }
};
```

In [`context.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/clients/c/tb_client/context.zig#L132-L135):

```zig
comptime {
    assert(@sizeOf(ClientInterface) == 32);
    assert(@alignOf(ClientInterface) == 8);
}
```

In [`packet.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/clients/c/tb_client/packet.zig#L136-L157):

```zig
comptime {
    assert(@sizeOf(Extern) % @alignOf(Extern) == 0);
    assert(@alignOf(Extern) == 8);
    assert(@sizeOf(Packet) == @sizeOf(Extern));
    assert(@alignOf(Packet) == @alignOf(Extern));

    // Asserting the fields are identical.
    for (std.meta.fields(Extern)) |field_extern| {
        // ...
        assert(field_packet.type == field_extern.type);
        assert(field_packet.alignment == field_extern.alignment);
        assert(@offsetOf(Packet, field_extern.name) ==
            @offsetOf(Extern, field_extern.name));
    }
}
```

**Key insight**: TigerBeetle does not assert alignment of incoming pointers at runtime — instead it asserts at compile time that all shared types have fixed, known alignment. This is a stronger guarantee: if you ship the library, the types are already verified.

---

### 2. Magic-Number Tagging Instead of Null Checks

Rather than checking `ptr != null` at every call site, TigerBeetle uses a **magic number embedded in the struct** to detect uninitialized or corrupted pointers. The init function sets the magic number **last**, as the final act of a successful initialization:

From [`context.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/clients/c/tb_client/context.zig#L51-L136):

```zig
pub const ClientInterface = extern struct {
    // ...
    const beetle: u64 = 0xBEE71E;

    magic_number: u64,

    pub fn init(interface: *ClientInterface, context: *anyopaque, vtable: *const VTable) void {
        interface.* = .{
            // ... all fields ...
            .magic_number = 0, // ← NOT set to beetle yet!
        };
    }
```

Then at the very end of the full `Context.init`, after everything succeeds:

```zig
        // Setting `magic_number` tags the interface as initialized.
        // Writing it at the end so that if `init` fails part-way through and the
        // user doesn't handle the error before using it, we'll still be able to validate.
        client_out.magic_number = ClientInterface.beetle;
    }
```

Every subsequent method uses this as a guard that returns a typed error (not panic):

```zig
pub fn submit(interface: *ClientInterface, packet: *Packet.Extern) Error!void {
    if (interface.magic_number != beetle) return Error.ClientInvalid;
    assert(interface.reserved == 0);  // ← assert only after magic check passes
    // ...
}
```

**Key insight**: Null is not the only invalid pointer. An uninitialized struct that came from external memory might be non-null but uninitialized. The magic number catches this. The `reserved == 0` assert catches ABI version mismatches from newer callers.

---

### 3. The `reserved` Field Assert — Detecting ABI Drift

Every FFI-boundary method asserts that reserved/padding bytes are zero. This is used to catch future-compatibility problems — if a newer caller fills in a field the library doesn't know about:

```zig
pub fn submit(interface: *ClientInterface, packet: *Packet.Extern) Error!void {
    if (interface.magic_number != beetle) return Error.ClientInvalid;
    assert(interface.reserved == 0);   // ← catches ABI mismatches
    // ...
}
```

In [`packet.zig`'s `assert_phase`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/clients/c/tb_client/packet.zig#L83-L87):

```zig
pub inline fn assert_phase(packet: *const Packet, expected: Phase) void {
    assert(packet.phase == expected);
    assert(packet.data_size == 0 or packet.data != null);
    assert(stdx.zeroed(&packet.reserved));  // ← reserved bytes must be zero
    // ...
}
```

The utility `stdx.zeroed` checks an entire byte slice for zero. This pattern permeates the codebase — superblock headers, WAL entries, state machine objects — all assert their reserved fields are zero before trusting any adjacent data.

---

### 4. Thread-Caller Assertions — Enforcing Call-Site Contracts

TigerBeetle uses a `threadlocal` variable to track whether the current thread is the IO thread or a user thread, and asserts this at every FFI vtable function:

```zig
threadlocal var thread_caller: union(enum) {
    user,
    io: std.Thread.Id,
} = .user;
```

All VTable functions called across the FFI boundary assert they're on the correct thread:

```zig
fn vtable_submit_fn(context: *anyopaque, packet_extern: *Packet.Extern) void {
    assert(thread_caller == .user);   // ← must be called from user thread

    const self: *Context = @ptrCast(@alignCast(context));
    // ...
}

fn vtable_deinit_fn(context: *anyopaque) void {
    assert(thread_caller == .user);   // ← same guard
    // ...
}

fn vtable_init_parameters_fn(context: *anyopaque, out_parameters: *InitParameters) void {
    assert(thread_caller == .user);
    const self: *Context = @ptrCast(@alignCast(context));
    assert(self.signal.status() == .running);  // ← post-init state assertion
    // ...
}
```

And the IO thread asserts the opposite when it starts up:

```zig
fn io_thread(self: *Context) void {
    assert(thread_caller == .user);  // starts as user, then transitions
    thread_caller = .{ .io = std.Thread.getCurrentId() };
    defer thread_caller = .user;
    // ...
}
```

---

### 5. Post-Initialization Invariant Asserts

After init completes and the state is live, subsequent methods assert the invariants they depend on. In [`client_register_callback`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/clients/c/tb_client/context.zig#L794-L812):

```zig
fn client_register_callback(user_data: u128, result: *const vsr.RegisterResult) void {
    assert(thread_caller == .io);
    const self: *Context = @ptrFromInt(@as(usize, @intCast(user_data)));
    assert(self.client.request_inflight == null);
    assert(self.batch_size_limit == null);  // ← must not be set yet
    assert(result.batch_size_limit > 0);   // ← server result must be valid
    // ...
}
```

In [`deinit`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/clients/c/tb_client/context.zig#L407-L426):

```zig
fn deinit(self: *Context) void {
    assert(thread_caller == .io);
    assert(self.signal.status() == .shutdown_completed);
    assert(self.submitted.pop() == null);
    assert(self.pending.pop() == null);
    maybe(self.eviction_reason != null);
    // ...
    assert(gpa.deinit() == .ok);  // ← no memory leaks
}
```

---

### 6. JNI: Alignment-Safe Pointer Recovery from External Memory

The Java client demonstrates the pattern most relevant to a Zig FFI receiving external memory. Java's `ByteBuffer` isn't guaranteed to be aligned, so TigerBeetle allocates with extra headroom and then uses `alignForward`:

From [`client.zig` (Java)](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/clients/java/src/client.zig#L449-L468):

```zig
pub fn get_client_from_buffer(env: *jni.JNIEnv, buffer: jni.JObject) *tb.ClientInterface {
    // The Java buffer isn't aligned,
    // so it is allocated with extra bytes to accommodate a potential `alignForward`.
    const buffer_capacity = env.get_direct_buffer_capacity(buffer);
    assert(buffer_capacity >= @sizeOf(tb.ClientInterface) + @alignOf(tb.ClientInterface));
    //     ↑ capacity must include both size AND alignment headroom

    const address = env.get_direct_buffer_address(buffer) orelse {
        JNIHelper.vm_panic(env, "Unexpected tb_client direct nio buffer.", .{});
    };
    return @ptrFromInt(std.mem.alignForward(
        usize,
        @intFromPtr(address),
        @alignOf(tb.ClientInterface),
    ));
}
```

**Key insight**: TigerBeetle does not assert pointer alignment after the fact — it asserts that the *buffer is large enough to accommodate alignment adjustment*, then actively aligns the pointer with `alignForward`. This is the canonical pattern for receiving externally-allocated memory of uncertain alignment.

Also note the JNI init pattern for global reflection state ([`load` in `client.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/clients/java/src/client.zig#L290-L370)):

```zig
pub fn load(env: *jni.JNIEnv) void {
    // Assert we are NOT initialized yet:
    assert(initialization_exception_class == null);
    assert(request_class == null);
    // ...

    // [do initialization] ...

    // Assert we ARE fully initialized:
    assert(initialization_exception_class != null);
    assert(request_class != null);
    // ...
}
```

Pre-condition null + post-condition non-null brackets the init operation, making double-init and partial-init detectable.

---

### Summary of Patterns for Your Zig FFI `State.init`

| Concern | TigerBeetle's approach |
|---|---|
| **Pointer alignment** | Don't `assert` it — `alignForward` + assert buffer has enough headroom (`size + align`) |
| **Null pointer input** | Use magic-number tagging, not null checks; null is not the only invalid value |
| **Post-init invariants** | Assert them in every subsequent function that depends on them, not just in `init` |
| **Reserved/padding bytes** | `assert(stdx.zeroed(&self.reserved))` at every use site |
| **ABI compatibility** | `comptime { assert(@sizeOf(...) == ...) }` — verified at build time, not runtime |
| **Thread safety** | `threadlocal` caller enum + `assert(thread_caller == .user)` at every exported function |
| **Double-init detection** | `assert(field == null)` before init; `assert(field != null)` after |
| **Partial-init on failure** | Set the "I am valid" signal (magic number / completion flag) **last** |

